Have a look at the following code. What is the console output going to be?

```java
abstract class Musician {
    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Musician";
    }
}
class Singer extends Musician {
    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Singer";
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Musician scooter = new Singer();
        System.out.println("What is your profession? " + scooter);
    }
}
```

What will be the output when you run the main method?

```java
interface Tameable {
    void tame();
}
class Mammal implements Tameable {
    @Override
    public void tame() {
        System.out.println("The mammal is being tamed.");
    }
}
class Cow extends Mammal {
    @Override
    public void tame() {
        System.out.println("The cow is being tamed.");
    }
    public void tame(String owner) {
        System.out.println("The cow is being tamed by " + owner);
    }
}
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Tameable cow1 = new Cow();
        cow1.tame();
        Cow cow2 = new Cow();
        cow2.tame();
    }
}
```

Take a look at the following code. Which of the statements is correct?

```java
abstract class Writer {
    public static void write() {
        System.out.println("Writing...");
    }
}
class Author extends Writer {
    public static void write() {
        System.out.println("Writing book");
    }
}
class Programmer extends Writer {
    public static void write() {
        System.out.println("Writing code");
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Writer w = new Author();
        w.write();
    }
}
```
